{"key":"processedPost-13799930","value":{"id":13799930,"first":13799813,"last":13819947,"when":1295244518,"utime":"01/17/11 08:08 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Theoretically the pressure at the bottom of a 3ft tall pot filled with water would be a around 16~ psi. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />No it wouldn't. A 1\" column of water three feet high does not weigh 16 pounds.&nbsp; 28\" W.G. is equal to 1 psi. <br /><br />Besides, the idea is way off base anyway.&nbsp; It's heat you need, not pressure.&nbsp; The pressure only raises the boiling point of the water, making it hotter.&nbsp; It wouldn't be any hotter at the bottom of a pot than on top.<br />RR","title":"Re: Tall pot instead of a pressure cooker?"}}